Q2 might be noisy for both names. Neither SoFi nor Robinhood is likely to wow on bottom-line metrics -- but that‚Äôs missing the bigger picture. These aren‚Äôt hype-driven fintechs anymore. If you're betting on platforms that digitally native consumers will actually use over the next decade, this is where the puck is headed.

Heading into earnings, here‚Äôs what I‚Äôm watching:

‚Ä¢ For SoFi: I want to see continued outperformance in the financial services segment -- this is the high-margin, fee-based engine that proves SoFi can scale beyond lending. Product adds above 1M and member growth above 700k would reinforce that the flywheel is intact. I'm also watching net interest margin closely -- if it holds near 6%, despite macro headwinds, it confirms their deposit funding advantage is real and durable. ‚Ä¢ For Robinhood: Robinhood needs to prove that monetization per user is trending up -- not just through trading, but via subscriptions, margin, and retirement flows. I‚Äôm also tracking the impact of Bitstamp ahead of full integration: are crypto volumes accelerating, and is there cross-pollination between core Robinhood users and the new international crypto base? And lastly, EBITDA margins above 50% would signal they're executing on growth without bloating the cost base.

Next week, everything aligns, and a significant amount of data/reports will be released. Any one of them alone would be important, but collectively, they can have a substantial impact on markets.

Our perception of markets/economy can change, IN EITHER DIRECTION, from Monday morning to Friday afternoon.

(I would argue that Friday's list is more important than Wednesday's)

-----

Monday
7:30 CT = The first part of the Treasury's Quarterly Refunding Announcement (QRA). This is the Financing estimate, or the amount of money they will need to borrow in the next quarter.
10:30 CT = 2-year Auction
Noon CT = 5-Year Auction (twofer because of the Fed meeting)

Tuesday
7:30 CT = Q2 GDP
Noon CT = 7-Year Auction (to finish the coupon auctions before the Fed meeting)

Wednesday
7:15 CT = ADP
7:30 CT = The second part of the Treasury's Quarterly Refunding Announcement (QRA). This part is the details of what they will issue (bills vs bonds).
1:00 PM CT = FOMC announcement and press conference (the big question is how many dissenters will we see, and does Powell "open the door" to a September cut?)

Thursday
7: 30 CT = June PCE

Friday
The first set of data for July ...
7:30 CT = July Payrolls
9:00 CT = July ISM
9:00 CT = July University of Michigan Sentiment Survey
All Day = July US vehicle (car/truck) sales

All Day = This COULD BE the biggest event of the week ...
